WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.330 --> 00:00:03.760
BRIAN KINDLER: Hi everybody.

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:06.120
Thank you for coming
to the second event

00:00:06.120 --> 00:00:07.610
in our Burma Series.

00:00:07.610 --> 00:00:08.710
My name is Brian Kindler.

00:00:08.710 --> 00:00:10.940
I'm the creator of Burma Series,
along with Google

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.050
Ideas, who has generously
sponsored this event.

00:00:14.050 --> 00:00:16.500
Today, we're lucky to have
with us Doctor Robert H.

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:19.990
Lieberman, a physicist from
Cornell University, whose 50

00:00:19.990 --> 00:00:24.270
year career has included the
creation of six novels, and

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:27.700
almost as many films, the latest
of which, "They Call it

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:30.720
Myanmar," was screened the other
night here at Google.

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:34.030
Dr. Lieberman is going to be
speaking with us today about

00:00:34.030 --> 00:00:37.480
contemporary Burma, and
answering questions.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:40.255
Please join with me to welcome
Dr. Robert Lieberman.

00:00:47.390 --> 00:00:48.850
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: I'm going
to run this like I run

00:00:48.850 --> 00:00:49.960
my physics class.

00:00:49.960 --> 00:00:53.740
Basically, I'm going to start
assuming nothing, and so it's

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.720
better to find out where
students are and take them

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.140
along, as opposed to--

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:01.140
how many of you have seen the
film "They Call it Myanmar"?

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:02.110
So some haven't.

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:03.270
You can stream it now.

00:01:03.270 --> 00:01:06.530
It's on all major digital
platforms, you know, Netflix,

00:01:06.530 --> 00:01:10.754
iTunes, and we have a website,
theycallitmyanmar.com.

00:01:10.754 --> 00:01:16.110
And anyhow, so Brian wanted me
to tell you about myself a

00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:18.950
little bit, so let me
introduce myself.

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:20.880
I have a number of careers.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:22.210
I teach physics at Cornell.

00:01:22.210 --> 00:01:25.280
I've been on the faculty there
for about 30 years.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:28.120
I've been writing novels for
even longer than that, and

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:30.045
short stories, and
I make movies.

00:01:30.045 --> 00:01:31.870
And I make movies because
we're really in the

00:01:31.870 --> 00:01:37.400
post-literate generation, so
I've done fiction films, I've

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.740
done a comedy called "Green
Lights," and I've done a film

00:01:40.740 --> 00:01:44.160
in Ethiopia during the
famine, various films

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:47.240
Anyhow, I'd like to talk to you
about Burma today, and I

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:49.430
have some notes, but I probably,
knowing myself,

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:50.680
won't use them.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:56.930
You know, I would like to look
at Burma as a Martian would

00:01:56.930 --> 00:01:59.970
look at it, or better yet, I'd
like to use Google Earth and

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:02.020
sort of zoom in on Burma.

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:04.670
And if you do that, and you're
sort of looking at Southeast

00:02:04.670 --> 00:02:10.229
Asia, if you look at the
countries surrounding Burma,

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:12.940
it's kind of interesting,
because none of them really

00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:15.550
are a beacon of democracy.

00:02:15.550 --> 00:02:16.380
There's Vietnam.

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.800
If you talk out against the
government, you're in trouble.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:21.550
Laos is a communist country.

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:23.520
I just got back from Cambodia.

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:26.900
Hun Sen, who's the Prime
Minister, was put in place by

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:29.935
the Vietnamese after the
Pol Pot slaughter

00:02:29.935 --> 00:02:32.840
of 3 million people.

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:36.370
Thailand, although it's
nominally a democracy, say

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:38.110
something bad about the king--

00:02:38.110 --> 00:02:40.150
somebody wrote a novel
mentioning something about the

00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:42.470
king they didn't like, they
threw them in jail.

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:49.030
And corruption is rampant in
all of these countries, so

00:02:49.030 --> 00:02:50.650
that's kind of the setting.

00:02:50.650 --> 00:02:52.620
Burma is different
in many respects.

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:55.420
Burma is kind of a unique
country, and I find it very

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:58.370
different from the rest
of Southeast Asia.

00:02:58.370 --> 00:03:05.950
And if you look at Burma from
above, if you start in the

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:09.120
north, you're in the foothills
of the Himalayas, and it's

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:10.200
snow covered.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:13.840
You start moving down south
and you hit jungle.

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.580
Then you hit sort of the arid
lands, and finally you're in

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.710
the delta, the rice growing
area, which is the lowlands.

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:24.320
This is a very, very
rich country.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:28.030
It has enormous gas reserves,
which, in

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:29.400
fact, are being tapped.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:31.396
Their offshore wells, they're
selling to all

00:03:31.396 --> 00:03:33.640
the neighboring countries.

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:39.450
So they have gas, oil,
gems, rubies, jade,

00:03:39.450 --> 00:03:41.150
lots of other minerals.

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:44.620
They have teak forests, and
they have agriculture.

00:03:44.620 --> 00:03:49.000
Burma at one point was really
one of the richest countries

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.600
in Southeast Asia.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:52.960
It was a big exporter of rice.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:54.210
It had the best universities.

00:03:57.080 --> 00:04:00.850
It was sort of a shining
example, and 50 years of

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:04.260
military rule have caused it
just to tumble to the bottom.

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:06.620
If there's a list of countries
and the poorest countries,

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:09.570
it's down there near
Egypt somewhere.

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:13.190
So I'd like to talk about
Burma sort of-- it's

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:14.500
very hard to do.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:17.050
Frankly, this is very difficult
for me because of

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:18.649
the complexities of
this country.

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:20.985
It's a country of 130
plus languages.

00:04:23.620 --> 00:04:28.490
There are nine major ethnic
groups, but really those break

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:29.740
up into subgroups.

00:04:32.050 --> 00:04:34.330
The primary religion,
I think 85% of the

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:35.960
population are Buddhists.

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:36.900
I'm an electrical engineer.

00:04:36.900 --> 00:04:38.150
I think we just got feedback.

00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:42.880
But there are Christians,
there are Animists--

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:44.780
I may show you the Animists--

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:47.050
and there are Muslims.

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:50.910
And so this is a incredibly
diverse country, and I don't

00:04:50.910 --> 00:04:54.460
know really what to do in
terms of presenting the

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:57.720
country to you, because there
are two complete visions.

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:01.070
There are the optimists, and
there are the skeptics, and I

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:05.650
don't know where the truth lies
in the realm of this.

00:05:05.650 --> 00:05:08.200
And I don't know where the
country is going, frankly, and

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:12.090
anybody who tells you they
know is probably lying.

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:16.080
This is a country of 60 million
people, and the

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:18.620
question of course, is why--

00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:21.770
when I did this film,
there was really a

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:22.870
high level of fear.

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:24.860
People were afraid to talk.

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:29.330
They were terrified, beatings,
torture, imprisonment.

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:33.930
I had one guy who is one of the
narrators in the film, and

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:38.595
he talks about what solitary
confinement, or was.

00:05:38.595 --> 00:05:43.450
It was essentially, they put you
into a concrete tube, all

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:46.080
right, and the tube is so
small that you couldn't

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:48.230
stretch out, you couldn't
stand up, and

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:49.690
they closed the end.

00:05:49.690 --> 00:05:53.090
That's solitary confinement, and
I think I could do about a

00:05:53.090 --> 00:05:58.760
minute and a half, and so this
gives you an idea of what they

00:05:58.760 --> 00:05:59.550
were capable of.

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:03.180
He mentions they put a bag over
his head with hungry mice

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:05.340
in it, and the mice were trying
to bite him, and he had

00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:06.410
to bite the mice.

00:06:06.410 --> 00:06:08.700
It's really Orwellian, which
is kind of interesting,

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:11.910
because George Orwell
spent time in Burma.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:15.760
So there's a sort of the
before and after.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:18.380
I've been there repeatedly,
and I was there for the

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:20.860
release of political prisoners,
and there was a

00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:21.760
massive release.

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:24.940
But there still are political
prisoners in jail, and they're

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:28.190
not political prisoners,
because they are in for

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:29.590
criminal violations.

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:33.240
And it's very hard to separate
those criminal charges were

00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:36.980
used essentially for
political reasons.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:40.260
The country's changing, and the
question is, I think-- and

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:43.100
by way, feel free to interrupt
and ask questions, in fact, I

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:46.070
prefer that--

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:47.650
why did this country change?

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:51.200
You're aware that Aung San Suu
Kyi was in 15 years of house

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:54.830
arrest, and suddenly
she's released.

00:06:54.830 --> 00:06:57.100
And why did this happen?

00:06:57.100 --> 00:06:58.630
Well, I think it happened
because

00:06:58.630 --> 00:07:00.400
of a number of reasons.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:04.770
I think it's economic, I think
the military was interested in

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:08.390
doing business with the West,
and I think the West was dying

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:10.140
to do business with Burma.

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:13.960
Before, Burma's main trading
partner with China, also

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:20.290
Thailand and India, but Burma
has a 1,200 mile border with

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:24.660
China, and so Western
companies have been

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:26.850
essentially drooling now
trying to get in.

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:30.910
They've got their sights set on
60 million people who are

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:32.890
going to buy toothpaste, and

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:36.600
television sets, and computers.

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:40.600
I think also the Burmese
military was nervous about the

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:42.720
Chinese influence.

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:46.150
I think also that the generals
wanted to be free to travel,

00:07:46.150 --> 00:07:48.410
and I think the generals wanted
to send their kids to

00:07:48.410 --> 00:07:53.340
Cornell, so it's a combination
of all these factors that

00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:56.960
caused, essentially,
the opening up.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:59.290
And when I was there in the
beginning, there was

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:02.400
essentially one internet portal,
you know, and it could

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:05.270
be pulled at any time.

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:06.830
I couldn't get onto the Cornell

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:08.360
server to get my email.

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:12.330
Interestingly enough, Google
Mail worked, Gmail worked.

00:08:12.330 --> 00:08:13.390
I don't know why.

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:15.420
It was really an exception.

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:19.100
And if you wanted to go to an
internet cafe, if you were

00:08:19.100 --> 00:08:22.170
Burmese you had to register, you
had to give them your home

00:08:22.170 --> 00:08:24.180
address, the name of
your school, the

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:25.880
name of your teacher.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:29.890
But what's interesting is that,
and there were walls

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:32.470
everywhere, but the kids
understood about proxy

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:36.049
servers, and so they were
downloading country and

00:08:36.049 --> 00:08:37.049
Western music.

00:08:37.049 --> 00:08:41.659
In other words, the wall was
porous, information was coming

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:44.420
in, so this is not
North Korea.

00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:47.680
This is, you know, somewhere
between the West, and

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:50.850
somewhere between North
Korea, potentially.

00:08:50.850 --> 00:08:54.560
So there was internet, and
of course now it's

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:56.580
really opening up.

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:59.660
So there's these two views, by
the way, of where is the

00:08:59.660 --> 00:09:00.380
country going.

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:03.830
Is it moving to democracy, or
is it essentially still

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:05.650
controlled by the military.

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:09.470
Well, there was a draft
constitution that was rammed

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:12.510
through at the time of Nargis,
this cyclone that hit, and

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:15.450
150,000 people were killed.

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:21.770
And the draft constitution
reserved 25% of the seats for

00:09:21.770 --> 00:09:22.630
the military.

00:09:22.630 --> 00:09:26.180
In addition to that, the USDA,
which is not the United States

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:29.060
Department of Agriculture, but
actually a political party,

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.140
many of those people are also
former military, so the

00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:35.760
parliament is very heavily
weighted towards the military.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:39.560
And Suu Kyi-- there was an
election now, a by-election--

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:43.640
she only won, in a landslide,
7% of the seats.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:47.190
And the question really
is, can Aung San

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:50.980
Suu Kyi affect change?

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:55.050
The skeptics feel like the
military is still in control.

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:56.860
The optimists feel like
they're on the

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:00.430
cusp of major democracy.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:05.380
Suu Kyi cannot become president,
because first of

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:11.270
all, if you have any relative,
if you or any relative have a

00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:16.900
British passport, then you can't
run for the presidency.

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:21.210
So there are a big election
coming in 2015, but the real

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:25.200
question is can Aung San Suu
Kyi run for that president.

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:28.180
I assume you all know who
Aung San Suu Kyi is.

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:28.720
You do?

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:32.550
OK, she's one of the narrators
of our film, and I keep

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.440
running into her.

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:38.510
There was a Film Festival in
Yangon, and I ran into her,

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:41.090
and I always say, hi,
do you remember me?

00:10:41.090 --> 00:10:44.420
And she says, yes, and then I
ran into her in the plaza.

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:46.550
They were giving an award
to her, and I

00:10:46.550 --> 00:10:47.960
said, hi, how are you?

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:50.540
And I think she's at this point
now where she thinks I'm

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:55.370
stalking her, but you have
to admire the woman.

00:10:55.370 --> 00:10:59.710
But there are people who really
don't like Suu Kyi, and

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:01.710
there are American scholars--

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:04.250
I showed this film at a meeting
of Burmese scholars,

00:11:04.250 --> 00:11:06.740
and there were some
very upset people.

00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:10.240
And they're upset because they
feel that Suu Kyi is sort of

00:11:10.240 --> 00:11:15.450
stealing the show, that she's
getting all these awards.

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:18.600
She went to Bangkok before the
president Thein Sein went, and

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:20.260
he had to cancel his trip.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:25.050
She's in the United States she's
at the UN, and on the

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:29.310
other hand, you have to really
admire this woman.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:32.570
She gave up her family.

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:36.700
She was on house arrest, her
husband was dying, and she had

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:37.490
to make a choice.

00:11:37.490 --> 00:11:40.250
Was she going to leave the
country and see her husband,

00:11:40.250 --> 00:11:45.390
or once she left, she
could never go back.

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:48.620
Does she stay, does she go,
and of course she stayed.

00:11:48.620 --> 00:11:51.910
She also gave up her children,
essentially, at a very tender

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:57.050
age, so this woman has made
enormous sacrifices.

00:11:57.050 --> 00:12:00.830
You know, when I filmed her,
she had just been released.

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:04.270
Our film was just about
finished, and I was furious at

00:12:04.270 --> 00:12:06.950
my editor, because he
was going so slow.

00:12:06.950 --> 00:12:10.240
We were working two years on the
editing of this film, and

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:12.260
I've never worked out
long in a film.

00:12:12.260 --> 00:12:16.160
And I was ready to strangle
David Kossack our editor, and

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:18.310
fortunately I didn't, because
she was released.

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:21.050
Then I flew back, and I had a
rare chance to sit with her

00:12:21.050 --> 00:12:23.500
and interview her.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:26.480
And I was determined not to
fawn over her, because

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:29.780
journalists in general tend
to fawn over her,

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:31.780
and so I didn't fawn.

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:34.650
But I went back later and I
looked at the rushes, and then

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:36.330
I started fawning.

00:12:36.330 --> 00:12:39.670
This woman is very,
very smart.

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:41.150
Unlike most politicians--

00:12:41.150 --> 00:12:44.300
if you interview George Bush
and you ask him A, he'll

00:12:44.300 --> 00:12:47.020
answer with Z, his
prepared thing.

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:49.440
It doesn't matter if it answers
the question or not.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:53.680
Suu Kyi is very, very smart,
and she's always listening.

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:58.780
And I think I surprised her
a bit, because I asked her

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:00.940
questions that she didn't
expect, because I

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:02.500
knew what we needed.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:05.760
So I started off, for instance,
saying like, tell me

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:07.460
a little bit about Burma.

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:08.380
And she said, what?

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:10.650
Yeah, I said, tell me
about the country.

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:12.390
I said, I know you can't
do that in 10 minutes.

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:14.420
She says, I can't do
that in 10 hours.

00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:19.170
Well, I said, tell me about the
diversity of the country,

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:22.500
and so actually I knew where we
were going, and fortunately

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:23.970
we were able to cut her in.

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:27.880
And it almost looks like we shot
her, and then we shot the

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:30.780
film around her, and of course
that's not the case, but I

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:32.550
think you have to
be the judge.

00:13:32.550 --> 00:13:34.560
She integrates into the film.

00:13:34.560 --> 00:13:36.350
Anyhow, she is very
impressive.

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:40.120
She's super smart, and she's
super articulate, and so I

00:13:40.120 --> 00:13:42.930
find it hard to dump
on her, frankly.

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:47.710
But there are real issues in
Burma, and the issues are the

00:13:47.710 --> 00:13:49.570
minority issues.

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.620
I don't know if you're
following the news.

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:56.300
There is a war going on with the
Kachin in the north west.

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:57.440
It's a fighting war.

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:00.810
The president has called for a
ceasefire, and said they will

00:14:00.810 --> 00:14:01.840
not attack any more.

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:05.740
In the meanwhile, gunships are
going in, and attacking the

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:09.640
Kachin, and so it shows you the
military is running the

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:12.530
show, not the president.

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:16.200
There has been a major problem
with the Rohingya in the

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:20.330
Rakhine state, and the Rakhine
state is sort of over here.

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:22.560
The Kachin are up here,
and the Rakhine are

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.920
somewhere over there.

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:29.980
And in the Rakhine state there's
a minority called the

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:36.390
Rohingya, and they are Muslims,
and a Burmese woman

00:14:36.390 --> 00:14:38.180
was raped by six Muslims.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:45.290
And this started a massive
retaliation on both sides, and

00:14:45.290 --> 00:14:47.020
the net result has been tens of

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:50.650
thousands of Rohingya displaced.

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:54.590
The Burmese, interestingly
enough, do not think of the

00:14:54.590 --> 00:14:59.560
Rohingya as Burmese, or
Myanmar, residents.

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:03.180
They originally came from
Bangladesh, and some of them

00:15:03.180 --> 00:15:05.110
have been there for
hundreds of years.

00:15:05.110 --> 00:15:10.100
They are actually stateless,
and they cannot send their

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:13.910
children to school, they can't
own land, and here's where we

00:15:13.910 --> 00:15:16.660
start to come into one
of the real problems.

00:15:16.660 --> 00:15:20.690
A friend of mine who runs an
NGO, or did a big one in

00:15:20.690 --> 00:15:25.570
Burma, said that Suu Kyi had a
choice, and she could have

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:31.150
either been sort of a moral
force, like Bishop Tutu, or a

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:36.350
politician, and she chose
to become a politician.

00:15:36.350 --> 00:15:39.530
And as a result of that, you
know you get dirty when you're

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:42.490
a politician, and you're
making compromises.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:46.320
Suu Kyi has asked about the
Rohingya, and she has really

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.320
not commented on them at all.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:51.470
Here is a woman who has really
fought for human rights, but

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:54.310
has steered clear of this,
because it's a hot potato.

00:15:54.310 --> 00:15:58.230
The Burmese, there's this
enormous hatred for the

00:15:58.230 --> 00:16:04.060
Rohingya, and this is a case
where she wants to run for

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:08.160
office, and run for president
potentially, and if she makes

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:10.720
a statement about the Rohingya,
she's going to lose

00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:11.860
a part of the electorate.

00:16:11.860 --> 00:16:17.240
So she could have stayed above
the fray, and she decided to

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:20.890
get into it, and I think now
you're seeing sort of the

00:16:20.890 --> 00:16:22.140
fissures that are occurring.

00:16:24.816 --> 00:16:27.000
There have been a number
of minority wars.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.110
The longest civil war on earth
was with the Karen, which are

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:35.320
a Christian group, essentially
in the eastern part of Burma,

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:37.550
and there is a ceasefire now.

00:16:37.550 --> 00:16:42.750
But in 1949, General Aung San,
the father of Aung San Suu

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:47.670
Kyi, managed to pull most of
the minorities together at

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:50.250
this Panglong conference.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:55.820
And they agreed that they would
work for independence

00:16:55.820 --> 00:17:00.020
from the Brits, and later on,
you know, they would form a

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:01.750
federation.

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:05.220
The question really is now
whether Aung San Suu Kyi can

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:08.280
hold this country together
with its 130 languages.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:08.839
It's amazing.

00:17:08.839 --> 00:17:14.010
If you go up towards the Golden
Triangle in the north,

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:16.150
in the-- have to just check my
directions here-- in the

00:17:16.150 --> 00:17:20.920
northeast, you can be dealing
with a tribal group, and go

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:23.960
over the hill and they speak a
totally different language.

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:26.900
They can't even speak
to one another.

00:17:26.900 --> 00:17:30.140
How do you hold a country like
this together is probably the

00:17:30.140 --> 00:17:32.290
big question.

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:35.410
When you speak about the
military, by the way, the

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:38.520
tendency is to think of it as
being monolithic, but the

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:42.230
truth of the matter is it is not
monolithic, that there are

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:45.740
some very progressive
generals.

00:17:45.740 --> 00:17:51.040
So there are fissures within the
military also, so although

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:53.290
the military does control
things, it is

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:55.060
not a single body.

00:17:55.060 --> 00:17:59.800
And one of the problems, of
course, with the opening up

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:04.060
is, essentially, resources.

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:08.650
The resources are controlled by
the military and by their

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:11.930
cronies, and one wonders
what's going to

00:18:11.930 --> 00:18:13.260
happen in the future.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:16.410
In other words, if you owned
all these resources, or you

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:21.670
had control, would you be
prepared to give it up, and I

00:18:21.670 --> 00:18:24.290
think I know the
answer to that.

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:25.800
Yes, a good question.

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:29.410
I think you're talking about the
cyclone in August that hit

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:31.800
in 2008, right?

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:37.360
What effect did that have on
the country opening up?

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:40.470
I don't know, but I heard that
the-- this is hearsay--

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:43.980
that Thein Sein, who became
president, was down there at

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:49.390
the time, and people say for
him it was life changing,

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:54.350
seeing the situation where
150,000 people died.

00:18:54.350 --> 00:18:59.150
At the time of the cyclone, the
military would not let in

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:01.580
relief supplies, which were
right there, essentially, in

00:19:01.580 --> 00:19:04.070
Thailand, and the United States
wanted to offload

00:19:04.070 --> 00:19:06.030
ships, and they wouldn't
let anybody in.

00:19:06.030 --> 00:19:06.990
I don't know.

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:08.750
The military is not
transparent.

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:10.800
You just don't know what
they're thinking.

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:14.900
They do not share any
information whatsoever, so a

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:18.550
lot of what goes on is really
conjecture about where their

00:19:18.550 --> 00:19:21.320
heads are at.

