DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN:
Oh my god.

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:27.900
That's a hard question,
because there

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:30.370
were ancient kingdoms.

00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:33.230
There is one kingdom that went
not just here, but it went all

00:19:33.230 --> 00:19:36.630
the way to Ayutthaya
in Thailand.

00:19:36.630 --> 00:19:41.210
I think that actually this
boundary is, and any historian

00:19:41.210 --> 00:19:46.300
can correct me, it is not Iraq
that was put together,

00:19:46.300 --> 00:19:47.450
essentially, by the British.

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:51.450
I think these are sort of
natural boundaries.

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:52.790
Any other questions, done?

00:19:52.790 --> 00:19:54.180
Yes?

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:56.290
You'll have to walk.

00:19:56.290 --> 00:19:58.490
Good.

00:19:58.490 --> 00:19:59.935
AUDIENCE: So I watched
the film the other

00:19:59.935 --> 00:20:01.700
day, and it was amazing.

00:20:01.700 --> 00:20:04.730
I know that some people's faces
were blurred out because

00:20:04.730 --> 00:20:08.150
of concerns for their safety,
but other people's weren't, so

00:20:08.150 --> 00:20:10.200
I was just wondering.

00:20:10.200 --> 00:20:11.820
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: Well the
ones that weren't blurred out

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:13.640
are all now in jail or dead.

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:14.890
I'm joking.

00:20:17.450 --> 00:20:21.790
Well, I blurred out the ones
that I thought were at risk.

00:20:21.790 --> 00:20:24.630
For instance, people on the
street, if you just shoot them

00:20:24.630 --> 00:20:27.490
it's fine, children are
basically innocent.

00:20:27.490 --> 00:20:32.150
You know, when I've done films
before, I like to have stars,

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:33.270
as I call them.

00:20:33.270 --> 00:20:36.490
In other words, I wanted
follow a family.

00:20:36.490 --> 00:20:39.440
I couldn't follow a family,
because whoever I followed

00:20:39.440 --> 00:20:41.710
would end up being arrested,
so this was a very

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:43.150
hard film to do.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:45.230
In other words, how do
you do a film and not

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:46.420
have stars in it?

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:50.100
And what we decided is that
the country was the star,

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:54.860
basically, and I was very, very
worried about the people

00:20:54.860 --> 00:20:56.580
who worked with me,
who helped me.

00:20:56.580 --> 00:21:00.040
You saw in the film, I got in
trouble in a number of cases,

00:21:00.040 --> 00:21:02.750
and I was worried about the
Burmese who were actually

00:21:02.750 --> 00:21:05.310
working with me and
helping me.

00:21:05.310 --> 00:21:06.450
I was teaching film there.

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:09.270
I was working with young film
directors, and when I would go

00:21:09.270 --> 00:21:12.120
to film, I would make it a point
of always asking them to

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:16.570
disappear, and then
meet them later.

00:21:16.570 --> 00:21:17.650
I was standing on the street--

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:21.550
I like to shoot crowds coming
at me, so I wanted people

00:21:21.550 --> 00:21:24.190
ebbing around me, so I planted
myself on a busy street and

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:25.600
started shooting.

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:30.020
And then some woman passed me,
and tapped me three times on

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:33.990
the shoulder and disappeared,
and then I knew I was in

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:38.580
trouble, so I quickly wrapped
up and just took off.

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:41.010
Nowadays, you can go in
and you can film,

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:42.150
crews are going in.

00:21:42.150 --> 00:21:43.360
But at that time--

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:46.570
I got in trouble for
filming vegetables.

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:48.540
I mean, it's bizarre.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:52.200
I got in trouble for filming the
National Library, and as

00:21:52.200 --> 00:21:54.940
you see in the film, this guy
keeps asking me to identify

00:21:54.940 --> 00:21:58.450
myself, and we wanted to know
my name, and want to have my

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:00.300
name card, and what's your name,
what's your name, and he

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:00.970
kept going.

00:22:00.970 --> 00:22:04.300
And I finally told him my name,
it's Shel Frequolm, and

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:08.230
I come from Stockholm, Sweden,
and I'm staying in the Park

00:22:08.230 --> 00:22:11.450
View Summit, which was the other
of town, and I took off.

00:22:11.450 --> 00:22:13.040
So I think they'll still looking
for Shel Frequolm.

00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:22.090
I think that the big question is
like, what's the future of

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:22.840
the country now?

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:25.360
Where is it going to go?

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:28.505
Is consumerism going
to take off?

00:22:28.505 --> 00:22:30.930
Are these people going to
lose their culture?

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:34.700
Is it going to become sort of
Bangkok, or is there really a

00:22:34.700 --> 00:22:37.410
sense of culture and history
where they can

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:38.780
preserve all that.

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:39.460
Yes, question?

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:42.360
AUDIENCE: Would you be
safe going back to

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:43.780
Myanmar to do more?

00:22:43.780 --> 00:22:45.190
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: Would
I be safe going back?

00:22:45.190 --> 00:22:46.090
I don't know.

00:22:46.090 --> 00:22:50.090
I tried to show the film at the
American Center, and the

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:51.590
Americans did not
want to show it.

00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:54.250
They were very nervous, and this
is after the opening up,

00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:57.280
so I showed it at the British
Council, which is part of the

00:22:57.280 --> 00:23:00.600
British embassy, and I showed
it one night, and the place

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:02.650
was packed with Burmese.

00:23:02.650 --> 00:23:06.140
And I left the next morning at
6:00 AM, and I haven't been

00:23:06.140 --> 00:23:09.220
back, so I can't answer
that question.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:11.670
But I did meet Thein Sein's
personal representative in the

00:23:11.670 --> 00:23:13.900
United States, and I gave him
a DVD, and I didn't even in

00:23:13.900 --> 00:23:17.955
charge him the $29.95,
so I don't know.

00:23:17.955 --> 00:23:19.090
Yeah, I don't know.

