00:32:20.620 --> 00:32:26.490
[SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:27.940
TRANSLATOR: I want to learn.

00:32:27.940 --> 00:32:28.780
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: Why?

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:33.970
[SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

00:32:33.970 --> 00:32:35.690
TRANSLATOR: I want
to be educated.

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:37.410
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: So one
of the themes that you keep

00:32:37.410 --> 00:32:41.260
running into, of course, is
education, and the education

00:32:41.260 --> 00:32:42.880
system was wrecked.

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:47.490
Originally, Burma had
the top universities

00:32:47.490 --> 00:32:48.640
in Southeast Asia.

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.650
Everybody came to
Burma to study.

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:56.370
I went to dinner with somebody,
and we were talking,

00:32:56.370 --> 00:32:59.610
and I kept on having to
say what, what, what.

00:32:59.610 --> 00:33:01.420
You know, I just couldn't
understand what they were

00:33:01.420 --> 00:33:04.800
saying, and finally I said, by
the way, what do you do for a

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:07.610
living, and he said,
I teach English.

00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:10.820
And as you see in the movie,
the educational system is

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:15.250
rote, basically, and the people
teaching in the schools

00:33:15.250 --> 00:33:16.955
English don't speak English.

00:33:20.060 --> 00:33:22.790
Probably the most pressing thing
for Burma right now is

00:33:22.790 --> 00:33:24.950
essentially rebuilding the
educational system.

00:33:24.950 --> 00:33:28.230
I think it's almost more
important than food at this

00:33:28.230 --> 00:33:32.460
point, so--

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:32.900
pardon?

00:33:32.900 --> 00:33:33.800
AUDIENCE: I have
a [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:36.000
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN:
Yeah, please.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.050
AUDIENCE: The education system
was actually stopped at one

00:33:38.050 --> 00:33:41.200
point in the '80s, where all
the schools were stopped.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:43.470
I have cousins and stuff that
were on their last year

00:33:43.470 --> 00:33:45.640
graduating with master's in
computer science and stuff,

00:33:45.640 --> 00:33:48.650
and they literally had to drop
out of school, had nowhere to

00:33:48.650 --> 00:33:53.040
go, and joined shipping
companies, climbing 100 foot

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:56.550
poles to make ends meet.

00:33:56.550 --> 00:33:58.580
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: My
understanding is that from

00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:01.940
what my Burmese friends
at the university,

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:03.320
bribery gets you there.

00:34:03.320 --> 00:34:07.270
And also at the high school, the
teachers supposedly teach,

00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:10.502
but then you have to hire
them after school.

00:34:10.502 --> 00:34:13.185
AUDIENCE: I was just
there in January.

00:34:13.185 --> 00:34:17.500
I was there for new year, and
Yangon felt like it was--

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:19.020
I mean, the only infrastructure
there was built

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:21.560
by the British, otherwise there
wasn't infrastructure.

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:26.440
So, I mean, to what extent they
invested, that's what's

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:27.900
in the country.

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:29.190
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: Yeah, but
I think it's very limited

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:29.850
what they did.

00:34:29.850 --> 00:34:32.190
I mean, there's some buildings
in Yangon that are built by

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:35.170
the British, but generally if
you travel around the country,

00:34:35.170 --> 00:34:37.440
the British didn't
do that much.

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:41.840
AUDIENCE: And then I remember
taking the highway down from--

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:42.310
what is it--

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:44.270
Mandalay, right from Yangon.

00:34:44.270 --> 00:34:46.380
What is the story behind
the highway, exactly?

00:34:46.380 --> 00:34:49.080
I heard numerous facts, but that
it was financed by the

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:52.400
US, and no-one's ever on it, so
it's like kind of this huge

00:34:52.400 --> 00:34:55.810
piece of infrastructure and but
the Burmese kind of don't

00:34:55.810 --> 00:34:58.250
use it or can't use it
because of the tolls.

00:34:58.250 --> 00:34:59.770
DR. ROBERT LIEBERMAN: I can't
answer that question, but I

00:34:59.770 --> 00:35:03.760
know there's a superhighway
that goes from Yangon, or

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:08.450
Rangoon, to Naypyidaw, which
is the new capital.

00:35:08.450 --> 00:35:11.540
By the way, the Burmese
government took all civil

00:35:11.540 --> 00:35:14.630
servants and moved them to
Naypyidaw, which is sort of

00:35:14.630 --> 00:35:18.240
the Brasilia of Myanmar.

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:22.080
And people think that's bizarre,
but if you look at

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:26.560
the history of the kings, what
they did is when a new king

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:29.260
came, they left the old city
and built a new city.

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:31.680
And I think the military must
be thinking of themselves as

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:35.860
sort of the new kings, and the
military, if you talk to them,

00:35:35.860 --> 00:35:38.000
they feel like they're doing
the right thing.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:39.650
They're helping the country.

00:35:39.650 --> 00:35:41.970
There are holding it together.

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:43.120
Yeah, question.

